      "text": "p. 224N48 The usual conception thinks exactly the other way round, because it interprets communication teleologically as being based on agreement. Then, of course, oral exchange (dialogue, discourse) must appear as the ideal form and all mechanization of communication through writing and printing as a sign of decay or as a stopgap."
